{
  "texts": [
    "Given S = {x 1,..., x m }, we consider the metric space (R S, L 2 S), where the metric L 2 S is defined asL 2 S (f, g):= 1 m m i=1 (f (x i) -g(x i)) 2for all f, g ∈ R S. Proof.",
    "Let k be a positive integer.",
    "For all 0 ≤ j ≤ k, define ϵ j:= B • 2 -j and let T j be a minimum ϵ j -cover of (F, L 2 S).",
    "It follows that |T j | = N (F, L 2 S, ϵ j).",
    "We let T 0:= {h} since L 2 S (f, h) ≤ B = ϵ 0 for all f ∈ F. Note that N (F, L 2 S, ϵ) is non-increasing with respect to ϵ, hence |T j-1 | = N (F, L 2 S, ϵ j-1) ≤ N (F, L 2 S, ϵ j) = |T j | for 0 < j ≤ k. Without loss of generality, we assume T k is a finite set (and hence all T j 's are finite sets), since otherwise N (F, L 2 S, ϵ) is unbounded for 0 ≤ ϵ ≤ ϵ k, in which case the integral is also unbounded and the inequality is trivially true.For each f ∈ F and 0 ≤ j ≤ k, let f j ∈ T j be a function such that f j covers f in T j, that is, L 2 S (f, f j) ≤ ϵ j."
  ]
}